<section class="block-section reflect">
  <span class="section-tag">Reflect</span>
  <h2>One question before you leave</h2>
  <p class="sub">Unit-close reflection. Five minutes. This one matters — it's about how you SEE differently, not what you know.</p>
  <div class="reflect-input">
    <strong>Prompt — unit-close metacognitive:</strong>
    <br>What's the most important thing about landscape I know now that I didn't three weeks ago?
    <br>How might I read a place differently in U3 (Plate Tectonics)? In U4 (Climate)? In U5 (Hydrosphere)?
    <br>If I returned to my chosen location 10 years from now, what specifically would I look at?
    <br><br>
    Type your answer in your Reflection Journal, or record a voice memo and drop it in your Drive folder.
  </div>
</section>

<section class="block-section concepts" style="margin-top:24px;">
  <span class="section-tag">Preview — Unit 3</span>
  <h2>Where we go next</h2>
  <p>Unit 3 asks: <strong>what's underneath the surface processes?</strong> Same Chennai foundation, but now you're looking at the rock and the boundaries below — what's making the Eastern Ghats Eastern, what brought the granites to Mahabalipuram, why the Indian Plate is moving northward into Eurasia at ~5 cm/yr, and why that movement matters for the hazards we'll spend Unit 3 on (earthquakes, tsunamis, volcanic chains). The landscape-reading muscle you just built is the foundation; the plates underneath are the foundation under that.</p>
  <p>The frameworks you used this unit (OPVL on geological sources, AI Documentation, landscape-as-record-of-processes) don't get re-taught in Unit 3. They get used. If something feels shaky from Unit 2, the <a href="/foundations/">Foundations</a> pages stay live all year — and the <a href="/units/unit-2/">Unit 2 landing</a> isn't going anywhere either.</p>
</section>
